    <h2>Who Should Use Canva?</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Social media managers</strong> creating daily content across platforms</li>
      <li><strong>Small business owners</strong> who can't afford a designer</li>
      <li><strong>Marketers</strong> needing quick visuals for campaigns</li>
      <li><strong>Presenters</strong> building decks without design skills</li>
      <li><strong>Content creators</strong> needing thumbnails, banners, and graphics</li>
      <li><strong>Teams</strong> collaborating on marketing materials</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Who Should Skip It?</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Professional graphic designers</strong> — use Adobe Illustrator or Figma</li>
      <li><strong>Users needing photorealistic AI images</strong> — use Midjourney or DALL-E 3</li>
      <li><strong>Those needing offline design</strong> — consider desktop alternatives</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Our Verdict</h2>
    <p>Canva remains the <strong>best free design tool</strong> in 2026. The addition of AI features like Magic Design makes it even more powerful. While the image generation isn't as advanced as dedicated AI tools, the convenience of having everything in one platform is hard to beat.</p>
    <p>If you create any visual content — social posts, presentations, videos, logos — Canva should be your first stop. The free plan is generous enough for most use cases, and Pro at $12.99/month is a no-brainer if you need AI features.</p>
